replies.text:
@ThinkingandTinkering what I did is ask friends, and yes they arent cheap, if you look at victron gear its a good bottom line (they are entirely different beasts from the cheap ones though) but I eventually took a middle path and got a fairly high quality small one with good specs, and its fantastic, I've left it on once or twice by accident and it will just run for crazy long times before killing the 640wh I gave it, on a 400w I think its close to 48 hours, and then it can also let me crank it to its max power an use all of the battery up in under two hours. Now that I do have an inverter, I'm looking at a more expensive one in the future because I was so impressed. You should absolutely do both dc and ac eventually, the DC gear ends up being invaluable battery rescue equipment and doesnt cost much

let's learn from each others mistakes because dc-dc is totally doable... here's what I learnt (you know this part already): 3-4m is fine, 20m is not
What was interesting is this: if you have a dc-dc with CC and CV, you absolutely under no circumstances do not want to activate the CC part of it while you have electronics on it... I lost two very expensive bits of gear before I figured it out, it might sound obvious but once you start tinkering its easy to forget it, I'm sure you'll probably look for something a little more permanent than what I did
